comment_regular_data.body:
@equalsraf Setting/getting is the wrong way to think about X11 clipboard. One does not set clipboard, it tells X server “I own the clipboard now”. When needed server requests owner “what is the clipboard contents, text please” (it may actually request different types of content).

For this reason msgpack-rpc is not the best way of handling the clipboard: what if Neovim is blocked by some long-running function? It is logical to have a separate event loop for the X11 clipboard thus, just blocking either main thread or specifically necessary structures (applicable only when using clipboard=autoselect*, for other actions main thread does not need to be bothered) when actually getting the clipboard contents.

Also for this reason one cannot notify when clipboard changes neither on Neovim side when it is owner (notification with a separate process communicating via msgpack-rpc is useless without pushing the whole clipboard contents and pushing the whole clipboard content is not the thing you want to do with `clipboard=autoselect*`) nor on other side when Neovim does not own it: the only way to determine that something changed is polling the clipboard because X server provides a way to find when _owner_ changes, not changes to clipboard content X server never knows.
